The proposed function puts the use case inside a Next.js/Prisma adapter. That is the main design error. `NextRequest`, `NextResponse`, `prisma`, and Prisma `Order`/`Invoice` types are all outer details; the approval rule and invoice-creation action should not depend on them.

Smallest production design:

```ts
// application/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceRequest = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceResult = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "REJECTED";
  lines: Array<{ amountCents: number }>;
};

export type NewInvoice = {
  orderId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export interface LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  byId(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null>;
}

export interface SaveInvoice {
  save(invoice: NewInvoice): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {}
export class OrderNotFoundError extends Error {}

function calculateInvoiceTotal(order: OrderForInvoicing): number {
  return order.lines.reduce((sum, line) => sum + line.amountCents, 0);
}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly orders: LoadOrderForInvoicing,
    private readonly invoices: SaveInvoice,
  ) {}

  async execute(request: CreateInvoiceRequest): Promise<CreateInvoiceResult> {
    const order = await this.orders.byId(request.orderId);
    if (!order) throw new OrderNotFoundError();
    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") throw new OrderNotApprovedError();

    const totalCents = calculateInvoiceTotal(order);
    const saved = await this.invoices.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: saved.id, totalCents };
  }
}
```

Ownership:
- Application/core owns `CreateInvoiceRequest`, `CreateInvoiceResult`, `OrderForInvoicing`, `NewInvoice`, and the two interfaces.
- Application/core also owns the approval check and total calculation.
- Prisma adapters own database query shapes and row mapping.
- Next.js adapter owns HTTP parsing and HTTP response mapping.

Where translation happens:
- Next.js route: `NextRequest -> CreateInvoiceRequest`, then `CreateInvoiceResult/errors -> NextResponse`.
- Prisma order adapter: Prisma row/include result -> `OrderForInvoicing`.
- Prisma invoice adapter: `NewInvoice -> prisma.invoice.create(...)`, then DB result -> `{ id }`.

Where concrete wiring belongs:
- In the outermost route/module boundary, for example:

```ts
const useCase = new CreateInvoice(
  new PrismaOrderReader(prisma),
  new PrismaInvoiceWriter(prisma),
);
```

That route should stay thin: extract `orderId`, call `useCase.execute`, map domain/application errors to HTTP status codes.

Two important boundary decisions:
- Do not make the repository return only approved orders. That would hide the approval rule in Prisma code instead of keeping it in application policy.
- Do not pass Prisma `Order`/`Invoice` types across the boundary. They are persistence models, not use-case models.

A minimal outer adapter sketch:

```ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const useCase = new CreateInvoice(
    new PrismaOrderReader(prisma),
    new PrismaInvoiceWriter(prisma),
  );

  try {
    const result = await useCase.execute({
      orderId: request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId")!,
    });
    return NextResponse.json(result, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotFoundError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "order not found" }, { status: 404 });
    }
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

This is the smallest design that keeps policy independent while avoiding unnecessary extra layers.
